Goal: The main goal of this document is to make a systematic literature review about the notion Printability from a rheology perspective

Specific goals:

  • Definition of printability from literature.
  • Map the rheology measurements used in 3D printing. Establish what correlations of rheology to printing process.
  • Identify requirements to consider for an open source hardware.

Reporting

MFI as a Printability quality Parameter

A polymer material characteristic such as branching degree, configurational stereochemistry, molar mass distribution and quantity of additives affect its flow behavior and therefore materials printing ability.

For controlling and predicting the whole printing process, specific material parameters can be measured, namely the melting temperature, the melt viscosity, the glass transition temperature, material heat capacity or its shear stress.

There are three conventional ways for measuring thermoplastic polymers viscosity:

  1. rotational rheometer
  2. high pressure capillary viscosimeter and
  3. melt flow indexer (MFI).

The first two methods provide material flow behavior in different conditions and therefore also give the plot of viscosity dependence on different measured material parameters, e.g.shear stress, pressure, melt flow rate, etc. Due to these plotted dependences, it is possible to determine the materials shear thinning behavior which is usually one of the first indications whether is the material printable or not. Based on these viscosity characterizations, the rotational rheometers, and high pressure capillary viscosimeters are the most commonly used methods for determining the material ability for 3D printing.

To the best of my knowledge, there are just a few papers in the literature (Web of Science), that presented only MFI from possible rheological methods as a printability quality parameter. In addition to measuring rheological behavior using MFI, other material characterization methods that could predict the materials 3D printing ability (e.g.Tg) were used.

The question of whether is MFI suitable indicator to predict materials 3D printability was tried to answer by a team of researchers from Ghent University. The melt flow index provides information about ease of the flow of the molten thermoplastic polymer. The higher the index is, the less is material viscous. According to the researchers, MFI correlates with the 3D printing process, interlayer adhesion and properties of the final printed product [1,2] Their research was focused on several commercially available PLA materials/filaments. It has been shown that for 3D printing of PLA filament is necessary to achieve at least MFI value of 10g/10min. This corresponds to a sufficient 3D printing process and final product quality. For achieving this minimal MFI value, it is possible to slightly adjust the melting temperature of the material [2]. Since the MFI values of commercial thermoplastics are usually given by manufacturers, this method could quickly and efficiently evaluate the materials viscosity and therefore indicate their 3D printability. And yet I have not found an article in which would describe using MFI characterization of recycled polymers for 3D printing.

References

  • [1] Shenoy, V.; Saini, D. Melt Flow Index: More Than Just a Quality Control Rheological Parameter. Part Il*. Adv. Polym. Technol. 1986, 6 (2), 125145.

  • [2] Sisi Wang, Lore Capoen, Dagmar R. Dhooge & Ludwig Cardon (2017): Can the melt flow index be used to predict the success of fused deposition modelling of commercial poly(lactic acid) filaments into 3D printed materials?, Plastics, Rubber and Composites, DOI: 10.1080/14658011.2017.1397308
